        "$:/language/Help/fetch": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/fetch",
            "description": "Fetch tiddlers from wiki by URL",
            "text": "Fetch one or more files over HTTP/HTTPS, and import the tiddlers matching a filter, optionally transforming the incoming titles.\n\n```\n--fetch file <url> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch files <url-filter> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-file <url> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-files <url-filter> <transform-filter>\n```\n\nThe \"file\" and \"files\" variants fetch the specified files and attempt to import the tiddlers within them (the same processing as if the files were dragged into the browser window). The \"raw-file\" and \"raw-files\" variants fetch the specified files and then store the raw file data in tiddlers, without applying the import logic.\n\nWith the \"file\" and \"raw-file\" variants only a single file is fetched and the first parameter is the URL of the file to read.\n\nWith the \"files\" and \"raw-files\" variants, multiple files are fetched and the first parameter is a filter yielding a list of URLs of the files to read. For example, given a set of tiddlers tagged \"remote-server\" that have a field \"url\" the filter `[tag[remote-server]get[url]]` will retrieve all the available URLs.\n\nFor the \"file\" and \"files\" variants, the `<import-filter>` parameter specifies a filter determining which tiddlers are imported. It defaults to `[all[tiddlers]]` if not provided.\n\nFor all variants, the `<transform-filter>` parameter specifies an optional filter that transforms the titles of the imported tiddlers. For example, `[addprefix[$:/myimports/]]` would add the prefix `$:/myimports/` to each title.\n\nPreceding the `--fetch` command with `--verbose` will output progress information during the import.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not fetch an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n\nThe following example retrieves all the non-system tiddlers from https://tiddlywiki.com and saves them to a JSON file:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\" \"[!is[system]]\" \"\" --rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[!is[system]]\"\n```\n\nThe following example retrieves the \"favicon\" file from tiddlywiki.com and saves it in a file called \"output.ico\". Note that the intermediate tiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" is quoted in the \"--fetch\" command because it is being used as a transformation filter to replace the default title, while there are no quotes for the \"--savetiddler\" command because it is being used directly as a title.\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch raw-file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico\" \"[[Icon Tiddler]]\" --savetiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" output.ico\n```\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/listen": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/listen",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "Serves a wiki over HTTP.\n\nThe listen command uses NamedCommandParameters:\n\n```\n--listen [<name>=<value>]...\n```\n\nAll parameters are optional with safe defaults, and can be specified in any order. The recognised parameters are:\n\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''credentials'' - pathname of credentials CSV file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''anon-username'' - the username for signing edits for anonymous users\n* ''username'' - optional username for basic authentication\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''authenticated-user-header'' - optional name of header to be used for trusted authentication\n* ''readers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to read from this wiki\n* ''writers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to write to this wiki\n* ''csrf-disable'' - set to \"yes\" to disable CSRF checks (defaults to \"no\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''tls-cert'' - pathname of TLS certificate file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''tls-key'' - pathname of TLS key file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n* ''gzip'' - set to \"yes\" to enable gzip compression for some http endpoints (defaults to \"no\")\n\nFor information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/render": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/render",
            "description": "Renders individual tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Render individual tiddlers identified by a filter and save the results to the specified files.\n\nOptionally, the title of a template tiddler can be specified. In this case, instead of directly rendering each tiddler, the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the title of the tiddler that is being rendered.\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--render <tiddler-filter> [<filename-filter>] [<render-type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be rendered\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]addsuffix[.html]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n* ''render-type'': Optional render type: `text/html` (the default) returns the full HTML text and `text/plain` just returns the text content (ie it ignores HTML tags and other unprintable material)\n* ''template'': Optional template through which each tiddler is rendered\n* ''name'': Name of optional variable\n* ''value'': Value of optional variable\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When referring to a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--render \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being rendered, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--render` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--rendertiddler` and `--rendertiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--render \"[!is[system]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]addsuffix[.html]]\"` -- renders all non-system tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles and the extension HTML\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler",
            "description": "Render an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddler` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType, defaulting to `text/html` and save it to the specified filename.\n\nOptionally the title of a template tiddler can be specified, in which case the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the tiddler that is being rendered (the first parameter value).\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler <title> <filename> [<type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n\nFor example, the following command saves all tiddlers matching the filter `[tag[done]]` to a JSON file titled `output.json` by employing the core template `$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile`.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[tag[done]]\"\n```\n"
        },

            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki (deprecated in favour of the new listen command)",
            "text": "Legacy command to serve a wiki over HTTP.\n\n```\n--server <port> <root-tiddler> <root-render-type> <root-serve-type> <username> <password> <host> <path-prefix> <debug-level>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation should only be used on a trusted network or over HTTPS.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password.\n\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nUsing an address like this exposes your system to the local network. For information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port. It can be useful to use an environment variable to pass the port number to the Node.js process. This example references an environment variable called \"MY_PORT_NUMBER\":\n\n```\n--server MY_PORT_NUMBER $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n"
        },

/*\
title: $:/core/modules/filters/regexps.js
type: application/javascript
module-type: filteroperator

Filter operator for regexp matching and returning result. All results are returned if global flag used. All sub-groups are returned if not global and sub-group hits are found.

\*/
(function(){

/*jslint node: true, browser: true */
/*global $tw: false */
"use strict";

/*
Export our filter function
*/
exports.regexps = function(source,operator,options) {
	var results = [],
		fieldname = (operator.suffix || "title").toLowerCase(),
		regexpString, regexp, flags = "", match, global,
		getFieldString = function(tiddler,title) {
			if(tiddler) {
				return tiddler.getFieldString(fieldname);
			} else if(fieldname === "title") {
				return title;
			} else {
				return null;
			}
		};
	// Process flags and construct regexp
	regexpString = operator.operand;
	match = /^\(\?([gim]+)\)/.exec(regexpString);
	if(match) {
		flags = match[1];
		regexpString = regexpString.substr(match[0].length);
	} else {
		match = /\(\?([gim]+)\)$/.exec(regexpString);
		if(match) {
			flags = match[1];
			regexpString = regexpString.substr(0,regexpString.length - match[0].length);
		}
	}
	try {
		regexp = new RegExp(regexpString,flags);
	} catch(e) {
		return ["" + e];
	}

	global = /g/.test(flags) ;

	// Process the incoming tiddlers
	if(operator.prefix === "!") {
		source(function(tiddler,title) {
			var text = getFieldString(tiddler,title);
			if(text !== null) {
				if(!regexp.exec(text)) {
					results.push(title);
				}
			}
		});
	} else {
		source(function(tiddler,title) {
			var text = getFieldString(tiddler,title), ret="";
			if(text !== null) {
				ret = text.match(regexp) ;
				if(ret !==null) {
					if(global) {
						results.push.apply(results,ret)  ; //DEBUG
					} else {
						// if there are  sub groups return sub groups START
						if(ret.length > 1)  {     // return sub groups
							results = results.concat(ret.slice(1)) ;
						} else { // if no sub-groups
							results.push(ret[0]);
						} 
					}
				}
			}
		});
	}
	return results;
};

})();






/*\
title: $:/core/modules/utils/dom/dragndrop.js
type: application/javascript
module-type: utils

Browser data transfer utilities, used with the clipboard and drag and drop

ELS: added dragImageType==="blank" (supresses drag image)

\*/
(function(){

/*jslint node: true, browser: true */
/*global $tw: false */
"use strict";

/*
Options:

domNode: dom node to make draggable
dragImageType: "pill" or "dom" or "blank"
dragTiddlerFn: optional function to retrieve the title of tiddler to drag
dragFilterFn: optional function to retreive the filter defining a list of tiddlers to drag
widget: widget to use as the contect for the filter
*/
exports.makeDraggable = function(options) {
	var dragImageType = options.dragImageType || "dom",
		dragImage,
		domNode = options.domNode;
	// Make the dom node draggable (not necessary for anchor tags)
	if((domNode.tagName || "").toLowerCase() !== "a") {
		domNode.setAttribute("draggable","true");		
	}
	// Add event handlers
	$tw.utils.addEventListeners(domNode,[
		{name: "dragstart", handlerFunction: function(event) {
			if(event.dataTransfer === undefined) {
				return false;
			}
			// Collect the tiddlers being dragged
			var dragTiddler = options.dragTiddlerFn && options.dragTiddlerFn(),
				dragFilter = options.dragFilterFn && options.dragFilterFn(),
				titles = dragTiddler ? [dragTiddler] : [],
			    	startActions = options.startActions;
			if(dragFilter) {
				titles.push.apply(titles,options.widget.wiki.filterTiddlers(dragFilter,options.widget));
			}
			var titleString = $tw.utils.stringifyList(titles);
			// Check that we've something to drag
			if(titles.length > 0 && event.target === domNode) {
				// Mark the drag in progress
				$tw.dragInProgress = domNode;
				// Set the dragging class on the element being dragged
				$tw.utils.addClass(event.target,"tc-dragging");
				// Invoke drag-start actions if given
				if(startActions !== undefined) {
					options.widget.invokeActionString(startActions,options.widget,event,{actionTiddler: titleString});
				}
				// Create the drag image elements
				dragImage = options.widget.document.createElement("div");
				dragImage.className = "tc-tiddler-dragger";
				var inner = options.widget.document.createElement("div");
				inner.className = "tc-tiddler-dragger-inner";
				inner.appendChild(options.widget.document.createTextNode(
					titles.length === 1 ? 
						titles[0] :
						titles.length + " tiddlers"
				));
				dragImage.appendChild(inner);
				options.widget.document.body.appendChild(dragImage);
				// Set the data transfer properties
				var dataTransfer = event.dataTransfer;
				// Set up the image
				dataTransfer.effectAllowed = "all";
				if(dataTransfer.setDragImage) {
					if(dragImageType === "pill") {
						dataTransfer.setDragImage(dragImage.firstChild,-16,-16);
					} else if (dragImageType === "blank") {			/* ELS */
						dragImage.removeChild(dragImage.firstChild);	/* ELS */
						dataTransfer.setDragImage(dragImage,0,0);	/* ELS */
					} else {
						var r = domNode.getBoundingClientRect();
						dataTransfer.setDragImage(domNode,event.clientX-r.left,event.clientY-r.top);
					}
				}
				// Set up the data transfer
				if(dataTransfer.clearData) {
					dataTransfer.clearData();					
				}
				var jsonData = [];
				if(titles.length > 1) {
					titles.forEach(function(title) {
						jsonData.push(options.widget.wiki.getTiddlerAsJson(title));
					});
					jsonData = "[" + jsonData.join(",") + "]";
				} else {
					jsonData = options.widget.wiki.getTiddlerAsJson(titles[0]);
				}
				// IE doesn't like these content types
				if(!$tw.browser.isIE) {
					dataTransfer.setData("text/vnd.tiddler",jsonData);
					dataTransfer.setData("text/plain",titleString);
					dataTransfer.setData("text/x-moz-url","data:text/vnd.tiddler," + encodeURIComponent(jsonData));
				}
				dataTransfer.setData("URL","data:text/vnd.tiddler," + encodeURIComponent(jsonData));
				dataTransfer.setData("Text",titleString);
				event.stopPropagation();
			}
			return false;
		}},
		{name: "dragend", handlerFunction: function(event) {
			if(event.target === domNode) {
				// Collect the tiddlers being dragged
				var dragTiddler = options.dragTiddlerFn && options.dragTiddlerFn(),
					dragFilter = options.dragFilterFn && options.dragFilterFn(),
					titles = dragTiddler ? [dragTiddler] : [],
			    		endActions = options.endActions;
				if(dragFilter) {
					titles.push.apply(titles,options.widget.wiki.filterTiddlers(dragFilter,options.widget));
				}
				var titleString = $tw.utils.stringifyList(titles);
				$tw.dragInProgress = null;
				// Invoke drag-end actions if given
				if(endActions !== undefined) {
					options.widget.invokeActionString(endActions,options.widget,event,{actionTiddler: titleString});
				}
				// Remove the dragging class on the element being dragged
				$tw.utils.removeClass(event.target,"tc-dragging");
				// Delete the drag image element
				if(dragImage) {
					dragImage.parentNode.removeChild(dragImage);
					dragImage = null;
				}
			}
			return false;
		}}
	]);
};

exports.importDataTransfer = function(dataTransfer,fallbackTitle,callback) {
	// Try each provided data type in turn
	if($tw.log.IMPORT) {
		console.log("Available data types:");
		for(var type=0; type<dataTransfer.types.length; type++) {
			console.log("type",dataTransfer.types[type],dataTransfer.getData(dataTransfer.types[type]))
		}
	}
	for(var t=0; t<importDataTypes.length; t++) {
		if(!$tw.browser.isIE || importDataTypes[t].IECompatible) {
			// Get the data
			var dataType = importDataTypes[t];
				var data = dataTransfer.getData(dataType.type);
			// Import the tiddlers in the data
			if(data !== "" && data !== null) {
				if($tw.log.IMPORT) {
					console.log("Importing data type '" + dataType.type + "', data: '" + data + "'")
				}
				var tiddlerFields = dataType.toTiddlerFieldsArray(data,fallbackTitle);
				callback(tiddlerFields);
				return;
			}
		}
	}
};

var importDataTypes = [
	{type: "text/vnd.tiddler", IECompatible: false, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		return parseJSONTiddlers(data,fallbackTitle);
	}},
	{type: "URL", IECompatible: true, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		// Check for tiddler data URI
		var match = decodeURIComponent(data).match(/^data\:text\/vnd\.tiddler,(.*)/i);
		if(match) {
			return parseJSONTiddlers(match[1],fallbackTitle);
		} else {
			return [{title: fallbackTitle, text: data}]; // As URL string
		}
	}},
	{type: "text/x-moz-url", IECompatible: false, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		// Check for tiddler data URI
		var match = decodeURIComponent(data).match(/^data\:text\/vnd\.tiddler,(.*)/i);
		if(match) {
			return parseJSONTiddlers(match[1],fallbackTitle);
		} else {
			return [{title: fallbackTitle, text: data}]; // As URL string
		}
	}},
	{type: "text/html", IECompatible: false, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		return [{title: fallbackTitle, text: data}];
	}},
	{type: "text/plain", IECompatible: false, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		return [{title: fallbackTitle, text: data}];
	}},
	{type: "Text", IECompatible: true, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		return [{title: fallbackTitle, text: data}];
	}},
	{type: "text/uri-list", IECompatible: false, toTiddlerFieldsArray: function(data,fallbackTitle) {
		return [{title: fallbackTitle, text: data}];
	}}
];

function parseJSONTiddlers(json,fallbackTitle) {
	var data = JSON.parse(json);
	if(!$tw.utils.isArray(data)) {
		data = [data];
	}
	data.forEach(function(fields) {
		fields.title = fields.title || fallbackTitle;
	});
	return data;
};

})();







/*\
title: $:/core/modules/widgets/draggable.js
type: application/javascript
module-type: widget

Draggable widget

ELS: added dragImageType param (for "blank")

\*/
(function(){

/*jslint node: true, browser: true */
/*global $tw: false */
"use strict";

var Widget = require("$:/core/modules/widgets/widget.js").widget;

var DraggableWidget = function(parseTreeNode,options) {
	this.initialise(parseTreeNode,options);
};

/*
Inherit from the base widget class
*/
DraggableWidget.prototype = new Widget();

/*
Render this widget into the DOM
*/
DraggableWidget.prototype.render = function(parent,nextSibling) {
	var self = this;
	// Save the parent dom node
	this.parentDomNode = parent;
	// Compute our attributes
	this.computeAttributes();
	// Execute our logic
	this.execute();
	// Sanitise the specified tag
	var tag = this.draggableTag;
	if($tw.config.htmlUnsafeElements.indexOf(tag) !== -1) {
		tag = "div";
	}
	// Create our element
	var domNode = this.document.createElement(tag);
	// Assign classes
	var classes = ["tc-draggable"];
	if(this.draggableClasses) {
		classes.push(this.draggableClasses);
	}
	domNode.setAttribute("class",classes.join(" "));
	// Add event handlers
	$tw.utils.makeDraggable({
		domNode: domNode,
		dragTiddlerFn: function() {return self.getAttribute("tiddler");},
		dragFilterFn: function() {return self.getAttribute("filter");},
		startActions: self.startActions,
		endActions: self.endActions,
		dragImageType: self.dragImageType, /* ELS */
		widget: this
	});
	// Insert the link into the DOM and render any children
	parent.insertBefore(domNode,nextSibling);
	this.renderChildren(domNode,null);
	this.domNodes.push(domNode);
};

/*
Compute the internal state of the widget
*/
DraggableWidget.prototype.execute = function() {
	// Pick up our attributes
	this.draggableTag = this.getAttribute("tag","div");
	this.draggableClasses = this.getAttribute("class");
	this.startActions = this.getAttribute("startactions");
	this.endActions = this.getAttribute("endactions");
	this.dragImageType = this.getAttribute("dragimagetype"); /* ELS */
	// Make the child widgets
	this.makeChildWidgets();
};

/*
Selectively refreshes the widget if needed. Returns true if the widget or any of its children needed re-rendering
*/
DraggableWidget.prototype.refresh = function(changedTiddlers) {
	var changedAttributes = this.computeAttributes();
	if(changedTiddlers.tag || changedTiddlers["class"]) {
		this.refreshSelf();
		return true;
	}
	return this.refreshChildren(changedTiddlers);
};

exports.draggable = DraggableWidget;

})();

Remove the margin in Firefox and Safari.\n*/\n\nbutton,\ninput,\noptgroup,\nselect,\ntextarea {\n  font-family: inherit; /* 1 */\n  font-size: 100%; /* 1 */\n  line-height: 1.15; /* 1 */\n  margin: 0; /* 2 */\n}\n\n/**\nRemove the inheritance of text transform in Edge and Firefox.\n1. @@float:right;[img width="130px" [images/eric3.png]]@@

''My name is Eric Shulman''.

Beginning in the early days of ~TiddlyWiki (April 2005), I have worked closely with its creator, Jeremy Ruston, helping to develop and improve ~TiddlyWiki's core functions. 

I am a key contributor and administrator of the online [ext[TiddlyWiki GoogleGroups|https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/tiddlywiki]] discussion forums, providing ongoing assistance to the worldwide ~TiddlyWiki community and have written more than 5000 detailed responses to individual questions posted online.  For several years I was also the lead developer and maintainer of the ~TiddlyWiki Classic codebase.

@@float:left;margin-right:1em;[img width="180px" [images/ttsnap_small.png]]@@ I am also the creator of ''[ext[www.TiddlyTools.com|http://www.TiddlyTools.com]] ("Small Tools for Big Ideas!")'', a popular collection of over 400 original plugins, scripts, themes, etc. for ~TiddlyWiki Classic that I have written and freely shared with the ~TiddlyWiki community to provide a rich variety of new features and enhancements that people can add to their ~TiddlyWiki documents.

I was born and raised on Long Island, NY (part of the New York City Metro area), and attended ''[ext[Carnegie Mellon University|https://www.cmu.edu/]] (CMU)'' in Pittsburgh, PA, where I focused on Computer Science, Cognitive Psychology, Sociology, Human Factors Design, and Artificial Intelligence. I received a ''Bachelor of Science in "Interactive Systems Design"'' from CMU in 1985.

As an undergraduate at CMU, I was privileged to work with some of the major luminaries in early software research and design, including [ext[Herbert Simon|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbert_A._Simon]], [ext[Allen Newell|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Newell]], [ext[James Gosling|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gosling]], and [ext[Raj Reddy|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raj_Reddy]].

During my early post-graduate years, I worked for several notable software development companies, including 
[ext[Honeywell Information Systems|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honeywell#Honeywell_Information_Systems]] and [ext[Lotus Software|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotus_Software]].  I was an integral member of the [ext[1-2-3 spreadsheet|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotus_1-2-3]] development team where I helped create the first GUI-based application interfaces for Microsoft Windows and IBM OS/2.

Professionally, I have been an ''independent software design consultant'' since 1998, living and working in Silicon Valley, where I apply more than 40 years of experience to provide analysis and design services for software development companies, with emphasis on ''information architecture'' and ''interaction/visual design standards'' to improve ease-of-use for new and existing software and online web products.

The right hand panel is called "the Sidebar".  The "Page Controls" buttons that appear at the top of the sidebar (e.g., "new tiddler", "control panel", "save changes", etc.) are not stored in a single tiddler.  Rather, each button definition has it's own tiddler, and these tiddlers are all tagged with "$:/tags/PageControls" to indicate that they should appear in that part of the Sidebar.

To define your own button:

# From the sidebar, click the "new tiddler" button.  This will open a new tiddler editor in the StoryRiver
# Enter a title for this tiddler (e.g., "MyButton")
# Add the $:/tags/PageControls tags to that tiddler.
# Next, enter your button definition into the text area, like this:<div>

```
<$button class="tc-btn-invisible"
   <$list filter="[<tv-config-toolbar-icons>match[yes]]">
      {{$:/core/images/spiral}}
   </$list>
   <$list filter="[<tv-config-toolbar-text>match[yes]]">
      <span class="tc-btn-text"><$text text="My New Button"/></span>
   </$list>
   <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-new-tiddler" tags="study" text={{MyButtonTemplate}}/>
</$button>
```
</div>
# Then, add a new field named "caption".  In this field, enter:<div>
``{{$:/core/images/spiral}} My New Button``
</div>
# and add another new field named "description".  In this field, enter:<div>
``Use this button to create a new tiddler with default content``
</div>
# Then, create a separate tiddler named "MyButtonTemplate", containing the default content you want to include in the tiddler.

Once you have defined these tiddlers, it will automatically appear as a Page Control at the top of the Sidebar.  You can re-position this button to put it the desired order alongside the other PageControls. To do this, open the $:/ControlPanel (click the gear icon in the Sidebar).

# The $:/ControlPanel has multiple levels of "tabs" for getting to the controls you need.  The top level of tabs is:<div>
``Info, Appearance, Settings, Saving Plugins, Keyboard Shortcuts``
</div>
# Select the "Appearance" tab (across the top).  This will show a second level of tabs:<div>
``Palette, Story View, Theme, Toolbars and Theme Tweaks``
</div>
# Select the "Toolbars" tab.  This will show a third level of tabs, displayed vertically on the left:<div>
``Edit Toolbar, Editor Toolbar, Page Toolbar and View Toolbar``
</div>
# Select the "Page Toolbar" tab.  This will display a set of checkboxes, showing all the buttons that are tagged with "$:/tags/PageControls".

If you've created your tiddlers correctly, your new button will appear at the bottom of this list.  To reposition it, just grab it with the mouse and drag it to move it within the list.






In addition to simple text formatting, you can ''use web-standard "inline CSS" (Cascading Style Sheet) syntax'' to achieve more complex formatting effects.  For example, if you want to show some text with styling applied using standard HTML syntax, you could write something like:

```
<div style="color:red;">
WARNING!  DANGER WILL ROBINSON!
</div>
```
To use the equivalent ~TiddlyWiki syntax, you would write:

```
@@color:red;
WARNING!  DANGER WILL ROBINSON!
@@
```
Basically, the ``@@...@@`` sequence is ~TiddlyWiki's way of defining a ``<div>...</div>`` (or a ``<span>...</span>``) //container// around your content.  The text ''immediately'' following the opening ``@@`` and ending with a semi-colon (;) still uses standard CSS syntax.

In either case, the results appear like this:
<blockquote>
@@color:red;
WARNING!  DANGER WILL ROBINSON!
@@
</blockquote>
You can also combine several CSS attributes together, separated by semi-colons (;) like this:

```
@@color:red;font-size:200%;font-weight:bold;line-height:100%;border:1px solid red;
WARNING!  DANGER WILL ROBINSON!
@@
```
which will appear like this:
<blockquote>
@@color:red;font-size:200%;font-weight:bold;line-height:100%;border:1px solid red;
WARNING!  DANGER WILL ROBINSON!
@@
</blockquote>
note: //''spaces matter!''... don't put any spaces __between__ the CSS attributes (i.e., following a semi-colon).  ''The first space after a semi-colon signals the end of the styles and the start of the text content''.  However, you can use spaces __within__ an attribute declaration (e.g., //``color: red;``// or //``font-weight: bold;``//), and some attributes (e.g., //``border:1px solid red;``//) have ''multiple parts that require the use of spaces'' within their declaration.//

As mentioned above, the ``@@...@@`` syntax is equivalent to the HTML ``<div>...</div>`` syntax.  However, using ``<div>`` always creates content that starts on a new line by itself.  If you want to do the same styles, but have the content appear ''inline'' with other text, you would use ``<span>...</span>`` in place of the ``<div>...</div>`` syntax, like this:

```
Then, the Robot said, <span style="color:red;font-size:200%;font-weight:bold;line-height:100%;border:1px solid red;">WARNING! DANGER WILL ROBINSON!</span> as it flailed it's tubular arms wildly.
```
and, in ~TiddlyWiki syntax, this would be written as:

```
Then, the Robot said, @@color:red;font-size:200%;font-weight:bold;line-height:100%;border:1px solid red; WARNING! DANGER WILL ROBINSON!@@ as it flailed it's tubular arms wildly.
```
Again, in either case, the results appear like this:
<blockquote>
Then, the Robot said, @@color:red;font-size:200%;font-weight:bold;line-height:100%;border:1px solid red; WARNING! DANGER WILL ROBINSON!@@ as it flailed it's tubular arms wildly.
</blockquote>
You can find ''many excellent CSS technical references online''.  For example, [ext[Mozilla|https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/border]] (a browser developer), offers this reference for the CSS "border" syntax: [ext[https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/border]].  You can use that site (and others like it) to look up lots of CSS goodies that you can then incorporate into your content, using either HTML or TiddlyWiki "wrappers".  This should give you plently to start playing with.

~TiddlyWiki's combination of unique features and functions provides several major benefits.

!!Overcoming the technical challenges
<<<
Unfortunately, most wiki systems use a complex combination of database and web server software to store and deliver their content to the user, and -- while it is possible to install these applications on a home computer -- it usually requires advanced technical skills, as well as great deal of time and effort, to properly set up and maintain such a system.

Fortunately, there is one application commonly used with most wiki systems that is //not// difficult to set up at home.  In fact, virtually every computer, tablet, and smartphone comes with some version of this software pre-installed, direct from the factory: it is __the web browser that you use to //view// the wiki content.__

~TiddlyWiki starts with the web browser's ability to render HTML/CSS content, and then uses Javascript -- the programming language embedded in most modern browsers -- to provide storage and delivery functions.

By combining these standard web technologies, ~TiddlyWiki has created a completely ''//self-contained, private, personal, and portable interactive wiki system//'' that is stored in a single file that can be loaded and run entirely inside your browser without installing any other software.
<<<

!!Flexibility
<<<
~TiddlyWiki is based on standard web technologies (HTML5, CSS, and Javascript) which provides a great deal of ''flexibility'' to customize the default layout and features of the ~TiddlyWiki interface, as well as the potential for using a wide variety of 3rd-party libraries, add-ons, and plugins to extend ~TiddlyWiki's core functionality.
<<<

!!Portability
<<<
Using commonly available web tech also provides ''virtually universal portability''.  ~TiddlyWiki is cross-platform compatible, with practically no installation, and runs virtually anywhere.  Using standard web tech allows you to view //and// edit your ~TiddlyWiki documents on almost any computer, tablet, or smartphone running a variety of different operating systems and software.
<<<

!!Privacy
<<<
~TiddlyWiki's self-contained operation means that the ''privacy'' of all of your information is under your direct control.  No remote hosting service is needed, so no one else sees your information (unless you want them to). 
Because ~TiddlyWiki documents are just simple files stored locally on your own computer, tablet, or usb stick, you can decide exactly when, where, what, and to whom you want to ''share your information''.  You can also encrypt your ~TiddlyWiki files for even more security.
<<<

!!Sharing
<<<
When you do decide to share your information, there are a number of options.  You can share a ~TiddlyWiki file by sending it as an ''email attachment'', or transfer it to a ''USB stick'' or upload it to a ''cloud file service'' (e.g., DropBox).  You can post your file to a third-party web hosting server to ''publish online'' (read-only), or use a local web server under your direct control for live viewing //and// editing.  You can also manage the distribution of your ~TiddlyWiki files through use of a ''source control service'' like GitHub.
<<<






* [[TiddlyWiki Distribution|http://www.TiddlyWiki.com]]
* [[TiddlyWiki github project|https://github.com/Jermolene/TiddlyWiki5]]
* Archives
* etc.






This chapter is ''a guide for users'' who are just getting started with ~TiddlyWiki. No prior experience with either [[TiddlyWiki5|http://www.TiddlyWiki.com]] or [[TiddlyWiki Classic|http://classic.TiddlyWiki.com]] is expected; however, some ''basic computer and Internet skills are assumed'', including the ability to:

<<<
* use a web browser to enter web addresses (URLs), click buttons and follow links
* use input forms to choose settings, edit text, and cut/copy/paste content
* upload, download and manage local files stored on your own device
<<<

General knowledge of web development tools and languages -- such as HTML, CSS and Javascript -- is not required for the topics covered in this chapter.

This chapter is ''a guide for authors and other content creators'' who want to build interactive presentations with ~TiddlyWiki.  No prior experience with either [[TiddlyWiki5|http://www.TiddlyWiki.com]] or [[TiddlyWiki Classic|http://classic.TiddlyWiki.com]] is expected; however, some ''basic computer and Internet skills are assumed'', including the ability to:

<<<

* use input forms to choose settings, edit text, and cut/copy/paste content
* upload, download and manage local files stored on your own device
<<<

In addition, although familiarity with web development tools and languages -- such as HTML, CSS and Javascript -- is not required, it can be ''__helpful for the topics covered in this chapter__''.

There are several ways to start creating or editing tiddlers in your ~TiddlyWiki document:

<<<
@@.floatleft {{$:/core/images/new-button}}@@
This button appears in the ~TiddlyWiki sidebar.
@@.clear @@

@@.floatleft {{$:/core/images/edit-button}}@@
This button appears in the toolbar of each tiddler that is displayed in the Story River.  Pressing this button begins editing that tiddler.
@@.clear @@

@@.floatleft {{$:/core/images/new-journal-button}}@@
This button //optionally// appears in the ~TiddlyWiki sidebar.  You can use it to create a new tiddler that is titled with the current date and tagged with "journal".  This is helpful for automatically creating a log of your activities.
@@.smaller <br>Note: __//this button is not shown by default, but can be configured to appear by selecting it from the [[Control Panel ViewToolbar|$:/core/ui/ControlPanel/Toolbars/ViewToolbar]] settings.//__@@
@@.clear @@

@@.floatleft {{$:/core/images/new-here-button}}@@
This button //optionally// appears in the toolbar of each tiddler that is displayed in the Story River.  Pressing this button creates a new tiddler that is automatically tagged with the name of the currently viewed tiddler.
@@.smaller <br>Note: __//this button is not shown by default, but can be configured to appear by selecting it from the [[Control Panel ViewToolbar|$:/core/ui/ControlPanel/Toolbars/ViewToolbar]] settings.//__@@
@@.clear @@
<<<

Once you start editing a tiddler, it's toolbar changes to show three icons: {{$:/core/images/delete-button}} delete, {{$:/core/images/cancel-button}} cancel, and {{$:/core/images/done-button}} done

* The fastest way to get started with TiddlyWiki is to visit http://tiddlywiki.com/#GettingStarted, and then download an "empty" TiddlyWiki document to your local device.

Optionally, you can also:

* Get TiddlyFox for local file I/O with FireFox
* Alternatively, get TiddlyDesktop for local file I/O

You can also download and install ''nodeJS'' to run your own local TiddlyWiki server.






The ''built-in'' "HTML5-compatible fallback saver module" uses the browser's native "download a file" handler to do the work of saving your changes to the local disk.  It works in the usual manner: there is a default "current directory" into which things will be saved and, when filenames "collide", the system adds a numeric suffix in parentheses.  Depending upon your browser, you can configure the download handling to "always ask".  In that case, instead of automatically saving a file with the number suffix, you can select the *existing* filename (i.e., without any number suffix) and then confirm when asked if you want to overwrite it.

It is important to note that, because of browser security restrictions, the "download saver" is the ONLY method that works regardless of your browser or system setup.
However, if you are using ~FireFox, then there is a browser-based addon called TiddlyFox that automatically adds secure local file I/O handling into the ~TiddlyWiki core code.  After installing TiddlyFox, ~TiddlyWiki can then write updates directly to your filesystem.  See http://tiddlywiki.com/#TiddlyFox for details.

Also note that, if you intend to use your ~TiddlyWiki file remotely (i.e., from an `http://` URL) or if you are going to be using it locally on other people's systems (e.g., read/save to/from a USB stick), then "download saving" may be the ONLY reliable option available to save your changes.

In this book, TiddlyWiki refers to revision 5.x or above.  Abbreviations and alternative names include: "TW", "TiddlyWiki 5.x" and "TW5".  Earlier versions of TiddlyWiki (2.x and below) are referred to as TiddlyWikiClassic or "TWC"






TiddlyWikiClassic refers to version 2.x or below of TiddlyWiki.  Alternative names include: "TWC", "TW2", and "TiddlyWiki 2.x".

Note: "TiddlyWiki" by itself is used when referring to //all// versions of TiddlyWiki, inluding both v2.x and below, and v5.x and above.  However, when referring exclusively to TiddlyWiki v2.x and below, the "Classic" or "TWC" designation is used to avoid confusion.






@@float:right;margin:0 1em; <a href="https://jermolene.com/" target="_blank">[img width="200px" [images/jeremy.jpg]]</a>@@
''These are personal reflections on the history and development of ~TiddlyWiki from [ext[JeremyRuston|https://jermolene.com/]].'' There is also a [[podcast|https://changelog.com/196/]] discussing ~TiddlyWiki's backstory.

! Origins of ~TiddlyWiki

Back in 1997 a colleague introduced me to [[Ward Cunningham's original wiki|http://c2.com/cgi/wiki]]. I was impressed that something so powerful could fit into just 700 lines of [ext[Perl|https://www.perl.org/]], and fascinated by the radical reimagining of security and permissions. Like many other developers, I took every opportunity I could to try out various wikis, and to explore their use at work.

The allure of the wiki for me was the feeling that it could eventually disrupt the prevailing paradigm of print-oriented documents and emails.

After watching people use wikis for a few years, I noticed that power users made extensive use of the ability to open multiple wiki pages at once in several browser tabs, making it easier for them to compare and review pages, to copy text between them and to act as a sort of queue of pages yet to be read.

I felt that this ability to manipulate multiple pages at once was central to the ability to refactor a wiki, and it is generally accepted that a wiki that is lovingly refactored tends to be more useful. And yet, standard wiki user interfaces have always been designed exclusively for the presentation and manipulation of single pages at once.

All of these thoughts came together when I saw GMail in April 2004, which used [ext[Ajax|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ajax_(programming)]] programming to cleverly blend individual emails into threaded conversations.

I started experimenting with [ext[HTML|https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML]] and [ext[Javascript|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript]] to explore the idea further. I'd had virtually no experience of either, just having put together some static pages and simple [ext[ASP|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Active_Server_Pages]] sites in previous lives. Getting my head around these client-side technologies was painful; like everyone else, I was horrified to discover how appalling were the incompatibilities and inconsistencies of web programming.

! Launch of ~TiddlyWiki

So, in September 2004 I released a primitive [[first version of TiddlyWiki|https://classic.tiddlywiki.com/firstversion.html]]. It was the smallest possible thing that demonstrated the idea: it was a simple, self-contained static 48KB HTML file.

The downside of writing the first version of ~TiddlyWiki in this way was that it made it completely impractical to use for editing - when you click 'save changes' it just pops up a window showing the data that would be saved if it were possible for an HTML page to write to the file system.

Much of the early feedback was that ~TiddlyWiki was neat, but that it would be more useful when it was possible to properly save changes. I was a little frustrated, as I thought I knew that it was impossible for an HTML file running in the browser to save changes to the local file system.

Within a few months I saw an experimental Firefox extension that enabled ~TiddlyWiki to save changes in the browser. Examining the code, I realised that the APIs that it used to write to the file system were actually available in ordinary HTML files - as long as they were loaded via a `file://` URI.

I adapted the Firefox code into the core of ~TiddlyWiki, and soon added a similar ability for Internet Explorer (making use of an old [ext[ActiveX|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ActiveX]] control that Microsoft distributed with Internet Explorer).

! Growth of ~TiddlyWiki

A major milestone in the growth of ~TiddlyWiki was the creation of "~GTDTiddlyWiki" by Nathan Bowers. He took the vanilla ~TiddlyWiki product and adapted it for the specific application of keeping track of tasks using David Allen's popular [ext[Getting Things Done|https://gettingthingsdone.com/]] methodology. ~GTDTiddlyWiki was an immediate hit, being enthusiastically greeted on websites like [ext[LifeHacker|https://lifehacker.com/]].

Over the next couple of years ~TiddlyWiki continued to grow in popularity, and gained new features and capabilities. Within a year I was able to support myself by performing bespoke development work on ~TiddlyWiki, notably working with wiki pioneer [ext[SocialText|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Socialtext]] on the ability to synchronise changes with an online server

! British Telecom (BT) Acquisition

In May 2007, [ext[British Telecom|https://www.bt.com/]] acquired ''Osmosoft'', my consultancy company. It was an unusual decision to acquire a company with a single employee and a tiny trickle of revenue - Osmosoft didn't even own the intellectual property in ~TiddlyWiki since I had handed it over to the non-profit [ext[UnaMesa Association|http://www.unamesa.org/]] to assure its future for the community.

BT's motivation was to help them understand community-based ecosystems. I joined the organisation as "Head of Open Source Innovation", taking responsibility for open source governance, and providing advice and expertise on how to participate in open source communities.

! Osmosoft and ~TiddlySpace

I built a team in BT under the name Osmosoft. Our purpose was to evangelise the benefits of open source, and to help other teams realise those benefits in practice. We also found that it was necessary to evangelise the use of the web in general, and web standards in particular.

Our approach was to focus on showing rather than telling. We worked with the ~TiddlyWiki community to extend the ecosystem and we built numerous internal systems for BT (some based on ~TiddlyWiki and some not).

Osmosoft's chief contribution to the ~TiddlyWiki community was the creation of ''~TiddlyWeb'' and ''~TiddlySpace''. ~TiddlyWeb was a robust, internet scale server for tiddlers that could also compose ~TiddlyWiki views of those tiddlers. ~TiddlySpace was an attempt to package ~TiddlyWeb into a more directly usable form.

! Leaving BT

By the end of 2011 I was increasingly feeling that I would be better placed to realise the potential of ~TiddlyWiki outside of the corporate confines BT. Accordingly, I left and started work as an independent developer, primarily working on a brand new reboot of ~TiddlyWiki in the shape of ~TiddlyWiki5.

! Development of ~TiddlyWiki5

I worked on new release of ~TiddlyWiki from November 2011. As a programmer, working on "version 2.0" of something that I had already written is a very attractive proposition. It means that the requirements were fully understood, allowing me to focus on evolving the architecture needed to support the desired functionality.

! The Future

Now that ~TiddlyWiki5 has finally left "beta" status behind, my hope is that it will have a long life. Because it only uses standard features of HTML5 and Node.js, there is no reason why it cannot be fully operational for many years to come. My goal is for it to last for at least 25 years.

//Jeremy Ruston, 20th September 2014//

how to share individual tiddlers and groups of tiddlers between documents

* using drag and drop
* exporting to stand-alone
* exporting to .tid files (for nodejs)






When ~TiddlyWiki starts, it automatically creates a set of special system tiddlers, found in the ''$:/info'' section of the shadow tiddlers.

These shadow tiddlers contains an assortment of values related to the browser and system in which the ~TiddlyWiki document is being used.  These values can be used to implement a more ''responsive layout using browser-specific custom CSS'', create links based on the current URL, etc.

Here's a list of the special system tiddlers that were created when //this// ~TiddlyWiki was loaded into your browser.  You can refer to [[https://TiddlyWiki.com/#InfoMechanism]] for more details about specific tiddler values:

<table class="width100" style="background:#eee;">
<$list filter="[all[shadows]prefix[$:/info]]">
   <tr>
      <td><<currentTiddler>></td>
      <td style="word-break:break-word;"><$view /></td>
   </tr>
</$list>
</table>

Notes:

<<<
The values in [[$:/info/browser/screen/width]] and [[$:/info/browser/screen/height]] are the number of __pixels__ for your display, and do not vary based on the browser's current window size.  Unless the browser window is currently //maximized//, these values will typically be greater than the actual browser window size.

To create layouts that automatically adjust to the current window size, CSS provides its own internal width and height values, using "vw" and "vh" units respectively, which have values between 0 and 100 units.  When defining the desired size of a page element, you can use "100vw" to refer to the current browser width, and "100vh" to refer to the current browser height.
<<<

There are also several additional $:/info tiddlers that are available if you ''install the "browser-sniff" plugin''.

<<<
To install this plugin, begin by opening the $:/ControlPanel and then select the "plugins" tab and press the big blue "Get more plugins" button.

This will display a modal dialog.  Press the big green "Open plugin library" button, and you will find an entry for:
<pre>Browser sniffing
$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/browser-sniff
5.1.21
</pre>
Press the "install" button to add this plugin to your current TiddlyWiki document.  Then save-and-reload for it to take effect. 
Once that is completed, you will find [[$:/info/browser/name]] and [[$:/info/browser/version]] now exist in your document.
<<<






{{||CoverPage}}






In this section, we will discuss how to get started using TiddlyWiki, including how to get either the empty stand-alone file, or the installation package for the nodejs version, as well as recommended choices for where to put the downloaded file(s), and how to set up the working directories.  Then, steps for startup (e.g., loading the file into your browser, or starting nodejs from the CLI) and configuring standard items (e.g., title) and options (control panel settings).

At the end of this section, the user should be ready to start exploring TiddlyWiki on their own system.

<<showLinks>>






@@.center ''//"Unless you've already seen ~TiddlyWiki, we guarantee you've never seen anything like ~TiddlyWiki."//''@@
@@.center.smaller - //"[[Discover TiddlyWiki|http://tiddlywiki.com/#Discover%20TiddlyWiki]]" on [ext[http://tiddlywiki.com]]//@@

<<showLinks>>
@@.floatright [img width=300 [images/twcomsnap.png]]@@

@@.larger Although most applications claim to be unique, __''~TiddlyWiki really //is// very different''__ from nearly every other application you may be familiar with.@@

The topics in this section will help you ''learn more about the overall concepts and general philosophy'' that helps ~TiddlyWiki deliver it's unique advantages.

These topics also suggest ''who might benefit from using ~TiddlyWiki'' as well as some of many ''ways that people use ~TiddlyWiki'' in their everyday lives to help manage their personal, social, commercial, and professional information.

This section also includes a brief explanation of the ''open source software development'' process that enables a wide variety of individuals and organizations to contribute to an ongoing continuous improvement process for enhancing and extending ~TiddlyWiki and sharing its unique abilities with a ''world-wide community of users, authors, designers and developers.''

Most wiki systems consist of a ''set of pages'', sometimes sub-divided into "sections" that can be edited individually.  Each page usually encompasses an entire topic of interest, with embedded images, and links to other related topics.  While all pages start out "empty", a typical wiki page can ''grow to be quite large'' over time, as more information is added.

Unlike most wiki pages, which can contain huge amounts of information, ~TiddlyWiki introduces the concept of ''~MicroContent'' which encourages people to ''break information into smaller pieces'' that can then be combined in a variety of meaningful ways, depending on the particular use-case needs.  This allows for greater flexibility.

In ~TiddlyWiki, the basic unit of ~MicroContent information is called a ''"tiddler"'' (see <$tiddler tiddler="WhatsInAName"><$link><<toc-caption>></$link></$tiddler>).  Each tiddler contains a set of "fields".

The standard tiddler fields include a ''title'' field that is used as a //unique ID key// for each tiddler, as well as a ''text'' field with content to be formatted and displayed, and a ''tags'' field that holds a list of keywords used for categorizing and searching.  An optional ''caption'' field allows you to provide an alternate description for the tiddler, separate from its title.

Each tiddler also has a ''type'' field that you can use to enter a specific [["MIME" media type|http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_media_type]] to enable special handling for specific kinds of data.  This allows ~TiddlyWiki to recognize, process and display a wide variety of different kinds of information, including ''embedded binary content'', such as images, audio, video, etc.

You can also define any number of ''extra fields'' to hold any data you like, stored as text, numbers, dates, multi-value lists, etc.  

In technical terms, each individual tiddler functions like a ''structured record'' in a database table and all the tiddlers in a document combine to form a complete database which can contain a mixture of different types of records.  This allows you to use ~TiddlyWiki to ''create your own database-like applications'', where each tiddler holds whatever details you want.

~MicroContent has a number of important benefits, especially when working with complex and/or dynamically changing information:

!!@@.resize [img[images/knowledge.svg]]@@ Knowledge Capture
<<<
When you are busy entering information, you don't want to have a lot of work to do to manage the process.  Instead, you want to keep your focus on the ''meaning'' of your information, not the ''method of entry''. Smaller pieces are easier to ''capture and rearrange later''.

//''This book was written using ~TiddlyWiki because it made it easy to capture the ideas and then organize them later''//.
<<<

!!@@.resize [img[images/discovery.svg]]@@ Discovery
<<<
~TiddlyWiki provides built-in functions (e.g., search, tagging) to help you discover new connections between your pieces of information.

You can search for ''literal text'' to find tiddlers that contain an exact match for specific pieces of information, or search for a ''text pattern'' that uses a powerful "[[regular expression|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_expression]]" syntax to match a wider range of information.

You can also search for ''keywords'' that have been entered as tags on individual tiddlers, allowing you to find tiddlers that fit specific categories of information.
<<<

!!@@.resize [img[images/connections.svg]]@@ Connections
<<<
~TiddlyWiki content can be linked and embedded in various ways to form meaningful groups.  You can define direct ''links between tiddlers'' as well as links to ''external resources''.

There is also a built-in ''directory of tiddlers'' ([[The SideBar]]) that provides a variety of options for what to show to give you instant access to all the information contained in your document.

As you enter information, you can use ''keyword tagging'' to construct a dynamically evolving hierarchical //tagsonomy// that can be used later to generate and present summary tables.  You can also use ''transclusions'' to combine your information by displaying content from one tiddler inside of another.
<<<

!!@@.resize [img[images/presentations.svg]]@@ Presentations
<<<
Once you have captured and connected your information in tiddlers, you will want to present it in ways that ''tell a story'' by //walking a path// through your information.

You can use the ''simplified wiki formatting'' to make your presentations look good, and can mix in standard "HTML5" and "CSS" syntax when you need to have more control over advanced display options.

You can also ''embed binary content'' (video, audio, graphs, animations, etc.) to provide a rich variety of information in addition to basic text.
<<<

!!@@.resize [img[images/transfer.svg]]@@ Knowledge Transfer
<<<
Different groups need different subsets of information.  ~TiddlyWiki's MicroContent approach lets you create a variety of ''information bundles'', customized for each audience.

New information can be easily added to existing references without affecting previous content.  You can send your document to an ''interaction designer'' or ''documentation specialist'' to help define the presentation and then hand-off the results to other authors and readers to enter and use that information.
<<<






* Tag topics with "<<currentTiddler>>" to add them to the top-level of the book.
* Edit the ``list`` field in //this// tiddler to define the order of the top-level topics.

\define ShowTitle()   <$set name="tv-wikilinks" value="no">{{!!title}}</$set>
\define ShowLink()    <$link><<ShowTitle>></$link>

\define showContents()
<$list filter="[!is[system]!prefix[TiddlyBook/]!prefix[TiddlyTools/]!tag[$:/tags/Image]] +[sort[]]">
   <$list filter="[<currentTiddler>tagging[]limit[1]]" variable="x">
      @@.larger ''__<<ShowTitle>>__''<br>@@
      <$list filter="[tag<currentTiddler>]">
         <<ShowLink>><br>
      </$list>
      <br>
   </$list>
</$list>
\end

\define showImages()
''__@@.larger Images<br>@@__''
<$list filter="[tag[$:/tags/Image]] +[sort[]]">
   @@.resize <$transclude tiddler={{!!title}}/>@@ <<ShowLink>><br>
</$list>
\end

<<showImages>>
</div>

\define ShowParts(pre)
__''<$text text="""$pre$"""/>''__<br>
<$list filter="[removeprefix[$pre$/]splitbefore[/]!suffix[/]] -[removeprefix[$pre$/]splitbefore[/]removesuffix[/]] +[sort[]]">
   <$list filter="[<currentTiddler>addprefix[$pre$/]!tag[$:/tags/Image]]">
      <<ShowLink>><br>
   </$list>
</$list>
<br>
<$list filter="[removeprefix[$pre$/]splitbefore[/]removesuffix[/]sort[]]">
   <$list filter="[<currentTiddler>addprefix[$pre$/]]">
      ''__<<ShowTitle>>__''<br>
      <$list filter="[prefix<currentTiddler>sort[]]">
         <<ShowLink>><br>
      </$list>
      <br>
   </$list>
</$list>
\end

\define ShowConfig()
__''~$:/config''__<br>
<$list filter="[prefix[$:/config]] -[is[shadow]] +[sort[]]">
   <nobr><<ShowLink>><br></nobr>
</$list>
\end

\define ShowModifiedShadows()
''__Modified Shadows__''<br>
<$list filter="[is[shadow]] -[prefix[$:/temp]] +[sort[]]">
   <nobr><<ShowLink>><br></nobr>
</$list>
\end

~TiddlyWiki can be used by people with a wide range of skills for a vast variety of purposes.  In general, they fall into at least one of four different categories: ''Readers'', ''Authors'', ''Designers'', and ''Developers''.

!!Readers
<<<
''Readers are consumers of information''.  Generally, they don't need any special technical skills (other than using a web browser).  Readers don't input information (except for searching), but simply navigate through information that has already been created by Authors.  For example, students can read assignments and reference materials that have been created or gathered by their teachers, while workers can read manuals, procedures, and policy guides and other business-related materials provided by their employers.
<<<

!!Authors
<<<
''Authors gather and enter new information'' into Tiddlywiki documents, but do not otherwise alter the underlying document setup.  The information they enter can be "raw" unformatted data or formatted content entered using general text editing and/or custom input forms created by Designers.
<<<

!!Designers
<<<
''Designers can customize screen layouts and install plugins'' to enhance and extend the standard, built-in features and functions of ~TiddlyWiki.  Using a mixture of macros, stylesheets, themes, etc., they can build ready-to-use custom "editions" of ~TiddlyWiki that can then be provided to Authors to fill in the details.
<<<

!!Developers
<<<
''Developers create new general purpose or use-case specific features and functions''.  They can use all the power of ~TiddlyWiki to implement custom-coded plugins that add new syntax, incorporate external function libraries, or make modifications to the programming of the ~TiddlyWiki core system itself to provide new capabilities for entering, viewing and manipulating specialized kinds of information.
<<<

The Control Panel lets you set a variety of standard configuration options for each TiddlyWiki document.

In general, when you change a setting, you will see the effects immediately, even while you are still typing your input!  However, some settings (e.g, changes to plugins) will require you to save-and-reload your document before they will be applied.

All settings are stored in special "system" tiddlers (with names that begin with "$:/..."), so any time you change settings, you will need to save your document to make sure those changes are preserved and will be used later when reload your document.

There are several tabs in the control panel:

<<list-links [tag[Setup]]>>






* Palette
* Story View
* Theme
* Toolbars
* Theme Tweaks







* Basics
* Advanced
** Editor Types
** Loaded Modules
** Tiddler Fields

\define changeLog() $:/state/ChangeLog

\define makelink()
<$link to="VersionInfo" tooltip="""last change:$(last)$""">''<$text text="""$(what)$ $(when)$"""/>''</$link>
([[TW$(version)$|https://tiddlywiki.com]])
\end

\define showVersion()
<$vars what={{VersionInfo!!version}}
       when={{$(changeLog)$!!when}}
       last={{{ [title<changeLog>get[text]removeprefix[*]splitbefore[*]removesuffix[*]] }}}>
   <<makelink>>
</$vars>
\end

<<showVersion>>

<div style="float:right">[img width=200 [images/sidebar.png]]</div>

The Sidebar provides access to all the controls and functions for managing your ~TiddlyWiki document.  You can use the Sidebar to create new tiddlers, browse existing tiddlers, search for text in tiddlers, change system settings, and save your changes.

!!!Show or Hide the Sidebar
The Sidebar can be shown or hidden by clicking the chevron in the upper right corner of the page.  The initial default is to show the sidebar.  The [[current Sidebar display setting|$:/state/sidebar]] is saved with your document and then automatically restored when that document is reloaded.

!!!Document Title and Subtitle
Each ~TiddlyWiki file allows you to define a [[SiteTitle|$:/SiteTitle]] and a [[SiteSubtitle|$:/SiteSubtitle]], which appear at the top of the Sidebar display as well as in the browser's titlebar.  These text items can be set from the [[ControlPanel]].

!!!Page Controls
Below the Title and Subtitle, the Sidebar displays a row of "toolbar buttons" that provides access to a variety of [[PageControls]].  By default, this toolbar includes buttons for creating a new tiddler, opening the ControlPanel, and saving your changes.  You can use ControlPanel settings (see [[ControlPanel/Appearance]]) to configure the toolbar to show additional toolbar buttons.

!!!Finding content
Following the toolbar, the Sidebar shows an input field, with a small "magnifying glass" button next to it.  This field is for entering search text.  As you type, the results of the search are automatically shown below the input field, providing a progressively narrower list of matches as you enter more text into the search input.  The search results are divided into two sections, to show "title matches" first, followed by a list of all matching tiddlers (including the title matches).  This makes it easier to quickly navigate to any tiddler by searching for a match on any text contained in it's title.

!!!Tabbed Lists
Below the search input field, the remainder of the Sidebar is used to display a set of [[Tabbed Lists]] that provide instant access to all the tiddlers in your document.  By default, the "Open" tab lists the titles of tiddlers currently displayed in the StoryRiver, while the "Recent" tab lists all tiddlers in reverse date order, with the most recently changed tiddlers shown first.  The "More" tab provides additional ways in which to organize and group the lists of tiddlers.






<div style="float:right">[img width=200 [images/storyriver.png]]</div>

Whenever you click on a tiddler link, it is opened and displayed in the Story River.  As you open more tiddlers they are added to the Story River.  There are various options for how to display the tiddlers in the Story River:

"Classic" view displays all opened tiddlers in a column, one after the other.  Clicking a tiddler link opens that tiddler below the current one (or scrolls to the tiddler if it is already displayed but not in view).  Clicking a tiddler link from the Sidebar (e.g., from a tabbed list or search results) opens the tiddler at the top of the story column.

"Pop" view display .... [TBD: HOW IS IT DIFFERENT FROM CLASSIC VIEW]


"Zoomin" view shows one tiddler at a time (the most recently opened tiddler).  Although only one tiddler is shown, all tiddlers that have been opened are actually still rendered into the Story River, and closing the currently displayed tiddler will re-display the previously opened tiddler (if any).

!!What is a Wiki?
In 1994, Ward Cunningham invented "[[WikiWikiWeb|http://c2.com/doc/etymology.html]]", which combined a web server and a database to enable people to quickly create websites without having to first plan and design all the content and links.  His system also made it possible for non-technical people to quickly edit, link and share information in a collaborative, group way, without having to first become experts in HTML and other web technologies.

In the years since then, the term "wiki" (shortened from ~WikiWikiWeb) has come to mean much more than simply a quick way to create websites.  In general terms, a wiki is an application (or system of applications) that provide several key features and functions:

<<<
@@.borderless
|<<showIcon images/ideas.svg>>|''//unstructured/unplanned creation of content//'' so you can capture your ideas as they occur without interrupting your workflow.<br>|
|<<showIcon images/editing2.svg>>|a simple way to ''//easily edit and format content//'' including text, links, images, tables, etc.<br>|
|<<showIcon images/discovery.svg>>|''//find and enhance connections between information.//'' through use of indexing, searching and other "discovery" functions.<br>|
|<<showIcon images/community.svg>>|groups of people can ''//share information and contribute content//'' to the same pages (though not necessarily at the same time).<br>|
@@
<<<

This combination of features makes a very ''powerful tool'' for working with many different types of information.  In particular, the unplanned authoring and simplified formatting makes it easy for people to ''create meaningful content'' without lots of technical assistance, while the discovery/collaboration features add a rich layer of extra value by helping to ''connect people and information'' in new -- and sometimes unexpected -- ways.

!!Public, Private, or Personal
There are many sites that run a variety of wiki systems that serve numerous different purposes.

[[Wikipedia|http://www.wikipedia.org]], the online encyclopedia, is perhaps the most well known ''__public wiki__'' on the web.  By using a wiki system, Wikipedia enables virtually anyone in the world to contribute their knowledge to the site, and it has become ''a reference work of enormous public value''.  As of January 2019, it contains nearly [[5.8 million articles with over 4.8 million views per hour|https://stats.wikimedia.org/EN/Sitemap.htm]] in the English edition alone, and the combined Wikipedias for all other languages greatly exceed the English Wikipedia in size, with [[more than 27 billion words in 40 million articles in 293 languages|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Size_comparisons]]!

There are also many organizations that run ''__private wiki__'' systems, providing for the varied information needs of businesses, researchers, social clubs, hobbyists, gamers, etc.  These systems are often installed on corporate and/or organizational computers that are typically maintained and updated either by professional IT personnel or by the most technically skilled members of the group.

Many people, after having experienced the way that wiki systems allow them to easily edit, categorize, search and present a wide range of shared information, would also like to be able to run their own ''__personal wiki__'' systems at home, without needing to trust their data to a remote server operated by other people.  Unfortunately, most wiki systems are relatively large and complex, and are often difficult to install and manage.  This is where ''~TiddlyWiki offers a distinct advantage''.

!!What Makes ~TiddlyWiki a Wiki?

~TiddlyWiki earns it's "wiki" label not only by being small and quick, by also by providing the key wiki functions directly in its standard core programming.

~TiddlyWiki includes a ''built-in editor'' for creating and modifying content using a special, easy to use formatting syntax. It also provides a powerful ''search function'', a ''keyword tagging'' system, and a multi-function "sidebar" with tools to easily manage, select and navigate between topics.

~TiddlyWiki can also be used for ''group collaboration''; however, this typically requires the installation and setup of a small utility application ([[NodeJS]]) that allows ~TiddlyWiki ''operate as its own webserver'' that permits users to remotely edit and share content directly from their web browser.






@@float:right;border:1px solid;[img width=300 float=right [images/tiddlereditor.png]]@@
This section describes the parts of the Tiddler Editor, and the procedures for creating a tiddler, including entering and formatting content, and adding images and links.

!!There are <$count filter="[tag<currentTiddler>]"/> topics in this section:
<<<
<<showItems "TiddlerEditor" ".larger">>
<<<






By default, the tiddler editor's text input area automatically adjusts to fit the number of lines of content.  When __editing a tiddler__, there is a button in the editor toolbar that can be used to limit the height of the tiddler text area input.

You can use CSS to limit the maximum height when __viewing a tiddler__.  To achieve this, create a tiddler tagged with <<tag $:/tags/Stylesheet>> and add the following line to that tiddler:
<pre>.tc-tiddler-body { max-height: 50vh; overflow-y:auto; }</pre>
You can, of course, adjust the max-height value to suit your specific needs.  You could also replace "max-height" with "height" which would force all tiddlers to be the same height, even if their content is shorter.

note: "vh" units refer to the current height of your browser window.  If you resize the window, the tiddler heights will adjust automatically.  If you use other kinds of CSS units (e.g., "em", "px", "in", "cm", etc.) then the tiddler heights will no longer be adaptive to the window height.






* CamelCase
** automatic links by recognizing upper/lower/number patterns
** //supposed// to make it less disruptive of the "flow" of writing
** in practice, it can lead to awkward names and odd grammar
* SquareBrackets
** use any text as link (i.e., title of target tiddler)
** bracketed links can include spaces and other symbols (except for brackets and vertical bar)
** use alternative display text for the link
* Links to "missing" tiddlers
** create links before the target tiddler even exists
** shown in italics to indicate that target is missing
** link opens "placeholder" view of missing tiddler so you can start editing
** pressing "done" creates the tiddler, italics are removed from link text

\define cookiename(prefix,suffix) $prefix$$(id)$$suffix$

<!--
This "CookieJar" binds cookie names with tiddler values.

When first rendered, cookie values update tiddler values (if different)
From then on, changes to the tiddler values update the corresponding cookie value to keep it in sync.
-->

<!-- TRACK ALL TIDDLYTOOLS CONFIG (except for ReadOnly) -->
<$list filter="[removeprefix[$:/config/TiddlyTools]!suffix[ReadOnly]]" variable="id">
   <$list filter="[title<id>addprefix[$:/config/TiddlyTools]]">
      <$cookie name=<<cookiename "TiddlyTools">> tiddler=<<currentTiddler>> />
   </$list>
</$list>

<!-- TRACK ALL SAVED SETTINGS (except for TiddlyTools pre-defined settings) -->
<$list filter="[tag[$:/tags/SavedSettings]!prefix[TiddlyTools]]" variable="id">
   <$cookie name=<<cookiename "TiddlyTools/SavedSettings/">> tiddler=<<id>> field="text"/>
   <$cookie name=<<cookiename "TiddlyTools/SavedSettings/" "/Tags">> tiddler=<<id>> field="tags"/>
</$list>






\define system()    [!is[system]!prefix[TiddlyBook/]!prefix[TiddlyTools/]]
\define titles()    [!title[Contents]!title[CoverPage]!title[Appendix]] -[title[Bibliography]] -[title[Glossary]]
\define appendix()  [!tag[Appendix]!tag[Legal]!tag[PartsList]]
\define images()    [!suffix[cover.svg]!suffix[legal.svg]]
\define emptyBook() $(system)$ +$(titles)$ +$(appendix)$ +$(images)$

\define makeEmpty()
<$button>
   remove Contents
   <$action-deletetiddler $filter=<<emptyBook>>/>
   <$action-setfield      $tiddler="TiddlyBook/RootTag" text="MyBook"/>
   <$action-setfield      $tiddler="MyBook"             text="{{CoverPage}}"
      caption="My Book" list="CoverPage Contents Appendix" NavBarTop="no" NavBarBottom="no"/>
   <$action-setfield      $tiddler="CoverPage"          tags="CoverPage MyBook"/>
   <$action-setfield      $tiddler="Contents"           tags="MyBook"/>
   <$action-setfield      $tiddler="Appendix"           tags="MyBook"/>
</$button>
<$list filter=<<emptyBook>>>
<li><$link><$text text=<<currentTiddler>>/></$link></li>
</$list>
\end

\define fav-config()      $:/config/TiddlyBook/Favorites
\define fav-is-favorite() $(fav-config)$##$(currentTiddler)$
\define fav-emptystar()   &#x2606;
\define fav-filledstar()  &#x2605;
\define fav-tip-addfav()  add '$(tiptext)$' to Favorites
\define fav-tip-remfav()  remove '$(tiptext)$' from Favorites

<!-- ADD/REMOVE ITEM FROM FAVORITES -->
<$set name="tiptext" filter="[<currentTiddler>has[caption]]" value={{!!caption}} emptyValue={{!!title}}>
<$reveal state=<<fav-is-favorite>> type="match" text="">
   <$button class="tc-btn-invisible" tooltip=<<fav-tip-addfav>>>
      <$action-setfield $tiddler=<<fav-config>> $index=<<currentTiddler>> $value=<<now>>/>
      @@.tt-favorite <<fav-emptystar>>@@
   </$button>
</$reveal>
<$reveal state=<<fav-is-favorite>> type="nomatch" text="">
   <$button class="tc-btn-invisible" tooltip=<<fav-tip-remfav>>>
      <$action-setfield    $tiddler=<<fav-config>> $index=<<currentTiddler>>/> <!-- DELETEINDEX -->
      @@.tt-favorite.show <<fav-filledstar>>@@
   </$button></$reveal>
</$set>

   <span title="$tid$">
      <$link><<toc-caption>></$link>
   </span>
</$tiddler>
\end






\define showIcon(tid,style:"float:left;margin-right:0.25em;font-size:250%;")

<$link to="$tid$">@@.resize <$transclude tiddler={{$tid$!!icon}}/>@@</$link>
@@
\end






\define showItem(tid,captionCSS:".larger",iconCSS,textCSS)

   <div title=<<currentTiddler>>>
      @@$iconCSS$    <$macrocall $name="showIcon"    tid=<<currentTiddler>> />@@
      @@$captionCSS$ <$macrocall $name="showCaption" tid=<<currentTiddler>> />@@
      @@$textCSS$    <$transclude field="description" />                      @@
      <div style="clear:left;"></div>
   </div>
</$tiddler>
\end

\define showItems(thistag,captionCSS,iconCSS,textCSS)

</$list>
</$vars>
\end
